{"cursor":"6099","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":" and its inscription (ÎÎÎ¡ÎÎÎÎ£, top right) on the \"Darius Vase\".]] (Berlin,\n Antikensammlung).]] from the Darius Painter's school (Berlin,\n Antikensammlung).]]\n\nThe 'Darius Painter' was an Apulian vase painter and the most eminent\nrepresentative at the end of the \"Ornate Style\" in South Italian red-figure vase\npainting. His works were produced between 340 and 320 BC.\n\nThe Darius Painter's conventional name Though many bear inscriptions, no\nvases in the group attributed to his workshop on the basis of their coherent\nstyle are signed. is derived from his name vase, the \"Darius Vase\", which\nwas discovered in 1851 near Canosa di Puglia and now on display at the Museo\nArchaeologico Nazionale, Naples (H3253). Many of his works, mostly volute\n[[krater]]s, amphorae and [[Loutrophoros|loutrophoroi]], are of large\ndimensions. He most frequently depicted theatrical scenes, especially ones from\nthe Classical tragedies by Euripides, The depiction of Darius on his name-\nvase is possibly derived in its details from the Persae of Phrynikos, C. Anti\nconcluded in 1952, and Schmidt 1960 follows him. However Oliver Taplin notes in\nPots and Plays, 2007, p.235-7, the only strong indications of tragic reference\nare Darius himself and the old man in paidagogos outfit on the plinth inscribed\nÎ ÎÎ¡Î£ÎÎ, who might be performing the messenger role. Taplin speculates that the\niconography of tragedy \"could be assimilated into other contexts without danger\nof confusion\", op. cit. p.237. and [[Greek mythology|mythological]]\nthemes. A number of mythological motifs not represented in surviving literary\ntexts are known exclusively from his vases. On other shapes, especiallypelikes,\nhe also painted as wedding scenes, [[eros|erotes]], women, and\n[[Dionysos|dionysiac]] motifs. In contrast to other contemporary painters,\nsepulchral scenes ([[naiskos vase|naiskos'' vases]]) by him are rare; where such\nmotifs occur, they are virtually always on the back of the vessel. Some of his\npaintings, like those on the Darius Vase itself, show historical subjects. ","linknr":218,"url":"Darius_Painter","recorded":1375071674,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Darius_Painter&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Darius_Painter&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-navigation","#p-search","/wiki/File:Darius-Vase.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/ba/Darius-Vase.jpg/220px-Darius-Vase.jpg","/wiki/File:Darius-Vase.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.22wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","/wiki/Darius_the_Great_of_Persia","/wiki/File:Altes_Museum_-_Antikensammlung_226.JPG","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9e/Altes_Museum_-_Antikensammlung_226.JPG/220px-Altes_Museum_-_Antikensammlung_226.JPG","/wiki/File:Altes_Museum_-_Antikensammlung_226.JPG","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.22wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","/w/index.php?title=Phrixos_krater&action=edit&redlink=1","/wiki/Berlin","/wiki/Antikensammlung_Berlin","/wiki/File:Fish_plate_Antikensammlung_Berlin_1984.54.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6a/Fish_plate_Antikensammlung_Berlin_1984.54.jpg/220px-Fish_plate_Antike